==Race==
[[File:University Boat Race Thames map.svg|right|thumb|[[The Championship Course]] along which the Boat Race is contested]]
Oxford were strong pre-race favourites, having won 16 of the last 17 races.<ref name=test>{{Cite news| work = [[The Times]] | title = Cambridge chase early lead to test dark blue's strength| first = Mike | last = Rosewell| date = 27 March 1993 | page=34| issue = 64603}}</ref>  Cambridge won the [[coin flipping|toss]] and elected to start from the Surrey station.<ref name=blast>{{Cite news | title = Cambridge's blast-off leaves Oxford in limbo| first = Christopher | last = Dodd | date = 29 March 1983| page=17| accessdate = 10 July 2014| work = [[The Guardian]]}}</ref>   Two minutes after the start, and in cold, overcast conditions,<ref name=williams/> Cambridge's cox Martin Haycock was level with Oxford's Jo Michels who occupied the number two seat in the Dark Blue boat.  Responding to a call to push on, Cambridge were clear upon reaching the Mile Post in record time, and moved in front of Oxford.<ref name=complete/><ref name=blast/>  Further record times were set as the Light Blues passed under [[Hammersmith Bridge]] and by Chiswick Steps before they passed the finishing post three-and-a-half lengths clear in 17 minutes.<ref name=blast/>  It was Cambridge's first victory since [[The Boat Race 1986|the 1986 race]] and just their second victory in eighteen years.<ref name=results/>  The winning time was the fourth fastest in the history of the event, surpassed only by Oxford in the [[The Boat Race 1991|1991]], [[The Boat Race 1984|1984]] and [[The Boat Race 1976|1976]] races, and was Cambridge's fastest time ever.<ref name=results/>  Cambridge's victory prevented the overall score from being levelled for the first time since 1929.<ref name=williams>{{Cite web | url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/rowing-light-blues-clear-water-revival-cambridge-at-last-tasted-victory-in-the-university-boat-race-yesterday-richard-williams-reports-1500324.html| work = [[The Independent]] | accessdate = 17 August 2014 | date = 28 March 1993| first = Richard | last = Williams | title = Light blues' clear water revival: Cambridge at last tasted victory in the University Boat Race yesterday }}</ref>

In the reserve race, Cambridge's [[Goldie (Cambridge University Boat Club)|Goldie]] won by nine lengths over Isis, their sixth victory in seven years.<ref name=results/>  Cambridge won the 48th Women's Boat Race by four-and-a-half lengths in a time of 6 minutes and 10 seconds, their fourth victory in five years.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://theboatrace.org/women/results | publisher = The Boat Race Company Limited| title = Women's Boat Race <U+2013> Results| accessdate = 9 July 2014}}</ref>

==Reaction==
The journalist David Miller, writing for  ''[[The Times]]'', described Cambridge's victory as "crushingly conclusive".<ref name=complete/>  Cambridge's [[Malcolm Baker]] said: "We knew we could do it after about 25 strokes."<ref name=complete>{{Cite news | title = Ruthless Cambridge complete ultimate humiliation | work = [[The Times]] | date = 29 March 1993 | page =21 | issue = 64604|first = David | last = Miller}}</ref>  Behrens explained "Our strength was that we were more uniform than Oxford.  We have proved that you do not have to be an Olympic champion to win the Boat Race."<ref name=blast/> The Oxford Boat Club president Pinsent conceded: "They put right a lot of mistakes they have made in the past, and they rowed outstandingly well."<ref name=gloat/>  Spracklen agreed: "Cambridge got too far away.  They were a better boat in that race.  All credit to them."<ref name=blast/>  Cambridge's number two, David Gillard, said "there was a lot of revenge out there".<ref name=darkclouds/>

Writing in ''[[The Independent]]'', the journalist Chris Arnot noted that the Cambridge crew had used [[creatine supplements]] in order to attempt to enhance their performance.  Used extensively at the 1992 Olympics, by athletes including [[Linford Christie]] and [[Sally Gunnell]],<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1993/Creatine-Said-to-Boost-Performance-And-It-s-Legal/id-ea59b25346d362d22d4beaf673af66fe | title = Creatine said to boost performance &ndash; and it's legal | first = Stephen | last = Wilson | agency = Associated Press | date = 8 May 1993 | accessdate=25 October 2014| publisher = AP News Archive}}</ref> and given to horses and greyhounds, it was believed to provide legal energy-enhancing effects to the crew.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/cambridge-boat-enjoys-the-creatine-effect-1500438.html | title = Cambridge boat enjoys the creatine effect| first = Chris |last = Arnot | date = 28 March 1993 | accessdate = 17 August 2014 | work = [[The Independent]] }}</ref>

